\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.21}{\ignorespaces An illustration of a possible arrangement of ten pilot-scale cavity experiments for Phase IV. The experiments are arranged in a circle with an approximate diameter of 50\nobreakspace {}meters. Each atomic beamline connected to the bottom of each cavity is approximately 10\nobreakspace {}m in length. The cavities themselves are designed to operate at 325\nobreakspace {}MHz and are approximately 11\nobreakspace {}m tall. The circular arrangement of cavities has some advantages when it comes to cancellation of fringe fields from neighboring magnets, which is important due to the small magnetic field magnitudes consistent with these CRES frequencies. The advantage of ten independent atomic sources and cavities is that there is no single point of failure for the experiment. If an experiment goes down for repairs the other nine may continue running. Figure courtesy of Michael Huehn at UW-Seattle. \relax }}{60}{}%
